Commentary.Commentary: We are set for the 2nd innings to get underway! The players of Sri Lanka make their way out to the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood are at the crease. Suranga Lakmal will start with the ball.

Right then! Sri Lanka have been bowled out for 386, with the pitch favouring spin heavily at the moment. The West Indies openers will be out in the middle soon and the hosts will look to attack them with spin. The visitors will have to believe in their ability and get off to a good start in order to keep the game in balance. Do join us for the second innings soon.

It was all Roston Chase and Jomel Warrican after the Lunch break. Both spinners bowled in tandem and after toiling away for a bit, got wickets as well. Chase has bowled consistently throughout the innings but Warrican really stepped it up in this session and ended up with 3 wickets. Chase picked up the final wicket and ended with a five-wicket haul, excellent performance from Windies' most reliable player in recent times. The visitors will be happy to have restricted their opponents under 400 but it's still a daunting task and their openers will have to give them the right start.

The hosts seemed to be set up for a big score at one point but it wasn't meant to be as the lower middle-order failed to muster up enough runs. Only Dinesh Chandimal got to 45 but rest of the batters didn't add much to the total. Chandimal, running out of partners, played a reckless shot and got himself out. This allowed the visitors to get the opening they were looking for and the Lankan tail was sent packing. In the end, the final pair of Lasith Embuldeniya and Praveen Jayawickrama did get some important runs, with Embuldeniya hitting a couple of lusty blows in the process.

What a session this has been for the Windies spinners! Play has moved quickly and West Indies are able to bowl out the hosts for under 400, which looked to be a formality at one point. Sri Lanka will be disappointed with how they've batted after the Lunch break.

The first session of Day 2 proved to be quite exciting as wickets tumbled and the hosts also scored at a decent rate. The upcoming session might just prove to be the most vital one so far, as we will get to know if the hosts plan on notching up quick runs and declaring or just keep on ticking away. The Windies, on the other hand will look to clean up the Lankan tail and get out to bat at the earliest. Join us soon for another riveting session of Test cricket.

This was by far the best session for West Indies so far in the Test match. Picking up 3 big wickets is what they would have wanted and they would be quite pleased. Gabriel, Chase and Warrican got a wicket each in the session. But the Windies still remain behind the curve. The pitch is starting to grip a lot more now and they have a pretty big mountain to climb against the Sri Lankan bowling attack. They would want to restrict the hosts to very few runs while taking the last 4 wickets soon.

Sri Lanka did lose Dimuth Karunaratne and Dhananjaya de Silva, who fell in a bizarre manner, quite early and the early wickets would have ignited hopes in the Windies camp. But those hopes were soon extinguished as Mendis and Chandimal stood in their way. Both these batters took their time at the start and once they got their eyes in, looked to accelerate. Mendis fell right before Lunch but Chandimal has looked good and would look to up the ante in the next session.

Another session saw Sri Lanka extend their dominance on this Test. They did lose three wickets but they have a pretty big score already and would look to press further and convert it into a massive score. West Indies did get three wickets in the session but they were made to work hard for it.

OUT! STUMPED! Immediate impact from Roston Chase and what a moment in the match this could prove to be! Chase flights it up beautifully, around the off stump and there's a bit of an extra bounce on offer. Dimuth Karunaratne just looks to keep it out on the off side but is undone by the flight and bounce as he presses forward. Joshua Da Silva, behind the stumps is quick to whip off the bails and seems confident. The third umpire takes a thorough look at it and concludes that the back foot was rooted on the line but no part of the boot was inside the crease and adjudges Karunaratne out. The skipper falls for an epic innings of 147.

We are ready for play! The umpires make their way out in the middle as the West Indies players are seen in a huddle. Out come the overnight batters for Sri Lanka, Dimuth Karunaratne and Dhananjaya de Silva. Jason Holder to start proceedings with the ball on Day 2.

PITCH REPORT - Farvez Maharoof is pitchside. He says that the pitch looks the same and there are hardly any marks. Adds that there is an area around back of a length from where some deliveries bounced and spun a bit extra. Mentions that the pitch looks good for batting overall.

Dimuth Karunaratne is down for a chat. He says that they want to put up a big score on the board and are eyeing 400. Adds that batting gets harder as the game progresses. Tells that first day is always a good for batting but this surface is a bit two paced and it wasn't easy to bat. Says that he was playing after 7 months and was eager. Adds that he knows how to get runs once he is set. Says that he wants to get big runs for his team and goes on to say that Galle is also his favourite ground.

It was a long, toiling day for the West Indies bowlers as all of them struggled to find any consistency in their line and lengths. Gabriel got them the breakthrough but he seemed to be all over the place. There was only one period of domination from the Windies bowlers and that was when Roston Chase got two wickets in quick succession. A quick update on the debutant, Jeremy Solozano who met with a freakish blow while fielding at short leg and was stretchered off, his scans show no structural damage but he was kept at the hospital overnight for observation. Can the visitors change their fortunes on Day 2 or will they be put under even more pressure by the hosts? We'll find out soon.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 2 of the first Test match between Sri Lanka and West Indies at Galle. Day 1 was a day that was dominated by the hosts, specially by their skipper Dimuth Karunaratne who brought up a stunning century. Karunaratne and Nissanka added 139 runs for the opening wicket which set the hosts up for a big score. In the last session the Lankan Lions lost couple of wickets in a row but Dhananjaya de Silva just came out and piled on more misery on the Windies bowlers as he raced away to a quickfire half-century. Dhananjaya de Silva has added 97 runs along with the skipper and the hosts seem to be firmly in command.
... DAY 2, SESSION 1 ...

8 bowlers in total rolled their arm for the Windies! They just tried everything but not much reward. Shannon Gabriel did get the one wicket but was not at his best. Roston Chase and Jason Holder were impressive but the latter bowled with little luck. Also, the fielding was not at its best as there were a few half chances which were not taken. All of this could well cost Windies if they do not manage to take early wickets on Day 2, they could well be in for another tiring day. The action will resume on Monday at 1000 local time (0430 GMT). But you can join us early for the build-up. Cheers!

Except for the start of the third session, the Lankans have dominated. The openers put up a 100-plus stand before Pathum Nissanka fell. Then there was a period where the Windies managed to keep it tight and Roston Chase did get a couple of breakthroughs but they could not capitalize on that. Dhananjaya de Silva and Dimuth Karunaratne then counter attacked, especially the former and they added 97 in no time. They are still not done and Sri Lanka will hope they can form a big partnership.

End of an excellent day for the Lankans! The partnership between Dhananjaya de Silva and Dimuth Karunaratne has given them a chance to set a big first innings score, probably bat them into a position where they can't lose the game. Their skipper's decision to bat first has been justified and it is their skipper who has led from the front.

Slightly shorter in length and on middle, Mathews nudges it to short leg.
Tossed up on middle, Mathews flicks but to mid-wicket.
Another maiden by Holder! On off, Karunaratne pushes it to covers.
From over the wicket now, angles it away, the line is well outside off. Left alone.
Solid this time! On off, Dimuth defends.

BEATEN! Dimuth Karunaratne was probably worried about the ball coming back in. This is a length ball outside off. Karunaratne looks to slash at it at the very end. Luckily for him, it goes past the outside edge.
Gets this one to shape back in from outside off. Karunaratne is solid in defense.
Angled in on middle, Karunaratne works it to mid-wicket.
Now stays in his crease and blocks this one on the stumps.
Mathews skips down the track, turns it into a full toss but mistimes it to mid on.
The series of dot balls end! Fuller and on off, Karunaratne pushes it down to long off and gets to the other end.
Slows it up and lands it around off, Dimuth plays it on the off side.
Really full and on off, Karunaratne jams it out to covers.
On middle, defended.
Good delivery to end a good over from Holder! A maiden! This one lands on a length, it jags back in after landing. Mathews looks to defend but it goes past the inside edge and hits him on his body.
Slightly shorter and into the body, Mathews tucks it on the leg side.
Another one on a length and on off, making the batter play. Mathews is solid in his defense though.
Back of a length and on off, Mathews pushes this one to covers.
Drags the length back and bowls it on middle, Angelo works it to mid-wicket.
Slightly fuller in length and around off, Mathews pushes it to covers.
Two consecutive maiden over for West Indies! Tossed up, full, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it out watchfully.
Looped up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne swings hard at it. The ball goes off the inner half onto the pads and lobs in front of the man at short mid on.
Four dots in a row. Full, around middle. Dimuth Karunaratne prods and blocks it back to the bowler.
Flighted, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and taps it out.
Floated, full and around off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it to point.
Tossed up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it towards short mid on.
A length ball, outside off. Mathews puts his bat out. The ball goes towards gully off the outer half. Another maiden over Holder.

Five dots in a row! This one certainly bounces. A length ball, outside off. The ball nips in and gets an extra bounce off the surface. Mathews looks to defend it out but misses and gets hit in the ribs.
Length ball, on off. Mathews pushes it towards cover.
A length ball, on the pads, Mathews flicks it to mid-wicket, but straight to the fielder.
Good length, outside off. Mathews leaves it alone for the keeper.
A length ball, on off. Mathews gets behind the line and defends it towards mid on.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Jason Holder.
Floated, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it back to the bowler.
On the pads, Matthews flicks it through square leg for a single.
Tossed up, on off, Matthews blocks it out watchfully.
Who will walk out now? It's going to be Angelo Mathews.

OUT! CAUGHT! A short leg comes in place for Oshada Fernando the new batter in the middle and it has done wonders for the West Indies. Chase gets his first wicket of the game and made sure his side starts the final session on a positive note. Quicker, around middle and leg. Fernando hangs back and flicks it to the right of short leg. Nkrumah Bonner is quick to react and grabs the ball sharply. West Indies players are delighted.
Commentary.Howout: c Nkrumah Bonner b Roston Chase

Commentary.Commentary: Short and outside off. The ball turns away. Dimuth Karunaratne goes back and cuts it through cover-point for a single.
Chase coming around the wicket. Tossed up, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pats it back to the bowler.

The final session is set to begin. West Indies players stride out to the middle. Followed by Dimuth Karunaratne and Oshada Fernando who walk out to bat for Sri Lanka. Roston Chase to start with the ball.
... DAY 1, SESSION 3 ...

Two sessions of Day 1 have gone by and both of them have belonged to the hosts. If West Indies want to get back into this contest they need to make sure to get as many wickets as they can in the final session. The hosts on the other hand, will be looking to keep things simple and just keep on scoring. An interesting final session is coming up.

Given it's a day one wicket, one does not expect the spinners to get too much out of the pitch but the Windies bowlers, as a bowling unit have been well under par so far. In the second session, hardly any chances were created and a lot of freebies were on offer for the Lankans. Gabriel came back into the attack and looked wayward but did manage to get the breakthrough. Instead of piling on the pressure, the Windies' bowlers kept on missing their mark and were punished.

The second session pretty much went like the first one. The hosts dominated with the bat as the Windies struggled to create chances. Both openers, Nissanka and Karunratne brought up well-compiled half-centuries. The skipper, in particular has looked very comfortable out there and is inching closer to a century. Nissanka did end up giving away his wicket after a 139-run stand with the skipper but apart from that Sri Lanka look to be on top of proceedings here.
Floated, full and on off. Fernando blocks it out watchfully. THAT WILL BE TEA ON DAY 1.
On middle and leg. Oshada Fernando prods and defends it to the leg side.
Tossed up, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it towards mid on and gets off the strike.
Flatter, on the pads, Dimuth Karunaratne glances it towards fine leg and collects a brace.
Looped up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne comes forward and taps it back to the bowler.
Flatter, around middle and leg. Dimuth Karunaratne helps it towards square leg.
Angled into the pads, Fernando tucks it to the leg side.
FOUR LEG BYES! Flighted, down leg. Fernando looks to flick it away but misses. The ball clips the thigh pad and goes towards fine leg. The ball races away to the boundary.
Tossed up, full and outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it through covers for a single.
Flatter and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne goes back and pushes it to cover.
Loopy ball, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it to short mid on.
Flighted, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it to cover.
Roston Chase (5-1-11-0) comes back into the attack.
Tossed up, full, around off. Fernando remains solid in his defense. 7 runs coming off this over.
Flighted full and on off. Fernando pushes it back to the bowler.
Looped up, full and on off. Fernando prods and defends it onto the pitch.
Full and on the pads, Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it towards mid-wicket for a single.
FOUR! Dimuth Karunaratne is motoring along really well here. Full and outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne drives it gently past extra cover. The ball goes through the gap and finds the boundary.
A couple of runs now! Flighted, full and on leg. Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it through mid-wicket for a brace. This also brings up 150 runs for the hosts.
Full length, on off. Fernando defends it to cover solidly off the front foot.
A length ball, outside off. Fernando comes across and defends it towards backward point off the outer half.
Full length, on off. at 123 kph, Fernando hangs back and pats it back to the bowler.
On the pads, Dimuth Karunaratne tucks it to mid-wicket for a single.
A length ball, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne taps it towards point.
A full-length ball, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it towards mid-wicket, but straight to the fielder.
Tossed up, full and on middle. Fernando defends it to cover.
NO BALL! Warrican oversteps and the umpire signals a no ball. Loopy ball, full and on middle. Fernando defends it out watchfully.
On middle, Fernando flicks it to the leg side.

DROPPED! Jomel Warrican could not react quickly. Flighted, full and on off. Oshada Fernando comes down the track and chips it to the left of the bowler. Warrican extends his arms but the ball slips out. Another chance goes begging.
Nicely bowled! Slowed up, around middle. Fernando has to go on the back foot and keep it out.
Stump to stump from Warrican and Fernando just blocks it out.
On middle, looking to spin it away from the right-hander. Fernando keeps it down on the leg side.
Mayers pullsw back the length again and bowls it around the off stump. Karunaratne punches it off the back foot towards cover.
A length ball, outside off. Karunaratne taps it towards backward point.
Fuller one, attacking the off stump. Karunaratne stays solid in defense.
Back of a length, around off. Karunaratne defends it off the back foot.
FOUR! Poor line from Kyle Mayers. Angles it towards the body, but it's down the leg side. Karunaratne pulls it behind square on the leg side and picks up another boundary.
Full and straight, pushed towards mid on.
Warrican slows this one up and bowls it on middle. Fernando keeps it out.
Slightly fuller, on middle and worked to short leg.
On a length, around off and this one turns away a bit. Fernando watchfully keeps it out.
On middle and leg, nudged towards mid-wicket.
On the pads, Fernando works it around the corner for a couple of runs.
Flatter one, on off stump. Fernando just manages to keep it out off the back foot.
Back of a length, on leg stump. Karunaratne defends it out onto the deck.
Full, around leg stump and going across the left-hander. Karunaratne blocks it back to the bowler.
Short ball, banged in around middle at 143 kph. Fernando hops back and dabs it down towards square leg for a quick single to get off the mark.
And again! Gabriel keeps pushing across and the ball ends up down the leg side. Fernando again misses the flick.
A length ball, at 141 kph and sliding down the leg side. Fernando looks to flick but misses.
Who will walk out now? Oshada Fernando it is.

OUT! CAUGHT! Finally the breakthrough comes for West Indies! Full and really wide, Pathum Nissanka goes chasing after it and pays the price. Nissanka looks to thrash it on the off side but gets the outside edge which goes straight to Rahkeem Cornwall at first slip. Cornwall takes a sharp catch and Shannon Gabriel has done the job for his team and breaks the opening stand. Can the Windies pile on a bit of pressure now?
Commentary.Howout: c Rahkeem Cornwall b Shannon Gabriel

Commentary.Commentary: On middle, pushed down to long on for one by Nissanka.
On off and caressed towards cover.
FOUR! Blackwood bowls another poor delivery and this time he does pay the price. Down the leg side, Nissanka gets down on one knee and paddles it into the fine leg fence.
Tossed up, around off. Karunaratne nudges it on the off side for a quick single.
Outside off and pushed towards the cover region.
Jermaine Blackwood comes into the atack now.
Loopy full toss, on off stump and that one had a boundary written all over it. Karunaratne though, hits it straight to extra cover.
Full and straight, pushed to mid on.
NO BALL! Gabriel will have to reload as he oversteps yet again. Length again, on off and this one keeps a bit low. Karunaratne does well to work it through cover-point for a run.
This is quick from Gabriel. A 144 kph fuller ball, just outside the off stump. Karunaratne happy to let that one through to the keeper.
Back of a length, at 144 kph and just outside off. Nissanka punches it off the back foot to deep point for a single.
A length ball, outside off and Nissanka shoulders arms.
Full and wide, squeezed out to deep backward point for one.
Hard-fought half-century for Pathum Nissanka. Back of a length, on middle. Nissanka hops and dabs it down towards short fine leg for a single. It's Nissanka's second fifty in Test cricket.
On off and kept out by Karunaratne.
Edged but safe! Flighted delivery, outside off and Karunaratne looks to cover drive. He gets an outside edge, through second slip and they come back for the second.
Tossed up, on middle and Nissanka uses his feet to get it down to long on for a single.
Fullish delivery yet again and Nissanka defends it out.
Full and straight, pushed down to mid on.
FOUR! Absolute gift from Rahkeem Cornwall. Dragged down, on middle and leg and spinning in. Nissanka has ample time to rock back and pull it into the backward square leg boundary.

FOUR! Streaky boundary as once again the rub of the green goes Karunaratne's way. Good-length ball, on off and slanting across the left-hander. Karunaratne looks to pull but gets an inside edge past the off stump and the ball races into the fine leg fence.
Length again, at 142 kph and around leg stump. Karunaratne dabs it down to short mid-wicket.

This time Gabriel drifts down the leg side. Nissanka looks to flick but the ball brushes the pads on it's way to the keeper.

Full and outside off, driven straight to the cover region by Nissanka.

DRINKS! Since the resumption of play after Lunch, it's been easy going for the Lankan openers. Both Nissanka and Karunaratne have been large untroubled and the skipper also brought up a half-century. The Windies' bowler have created minimal chances and have been left toiling hard in the sun. Can this change after the break?
Tossed up, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out with soft hands.

A huge appeal for lbw but the umpire is unmoved. Quicker, full and around leg. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to sweep it away but misses. He gets hit on the pads. Cornwall pleads but the umpire says no. West Indies skipper, Kraigg Brathwaite had a lot to think about, as they only have a single review left now. Hence, he decides to go against it.

Full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out solidly.
Flighted, around off. The ball grips and turns away. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and pushes it to point.

Good-length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne punches it towards point. Is Jason Holder on his way to his fifth maiden?
Make it 4 dots! On a length, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne taps it towards point. He wanted a single, but the fielder was quick to get to the ball.
Three dots on the trot! A full-length ball, around middle and off. Dimuth Karunaratne works it towards mid on.
On a length, outside off, at 126 kph. Dimuth Karunaratne comes across and lets it go to the keeper.
A length ball, outside off. Angling across the left-hander. Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone for the keeper.
Fatter and around off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it towards cover. The fielder dives to his right to make a half stop. They take one.
Tossed up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne remains solid and taps the ball out.
Full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it out watchfully.
Floated, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it on to the pitch.
Touch short, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and cuts it towards point.
Loopy ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne lets it sail past him.
This is the fourth maiden over for Holder in this innings. Brilliant bowling by him. A good-length ball, outside off. The ball nips in a bit. Pathum Nissanka prods and shoulders his arms.
Full and on off. Nissanka drives it to cover, straight to the fielder.

A length ball, on off. Nissanka defends it back to the bowler with a straight bat.

Back of a length, around off. Nissanka hops inside the crease and blocks it back to the bowler.

Full and on middle. Nissanka comes forward and pushes it towards mid on.

Just a change of gloves for the skipper. It's pretty hot and humid out there.
Good-length ball, outside off, Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone for the keeper.
A length ball, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and pushes it towards mid off.
FOUR! EDGY! Good-length ball, around off, angling across the left-hander. Dimuth Karunaratne plays it late and with soft hands. The ball goes through the slip cordon and races away to the fence.
Fuller, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it towards mid off.
On a length, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne is a bit early into his stroke this time. The ball was a bit aerial but it eludes the man at short extra cover.
A length ball, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and blocks it to the off side.
On off, Nissanka blocks it on to the pitch.
Floated, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it towards mid off and gets a single.
Full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne remains solid in his defense.
Tossed up, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it off solidly.

FOUR! Nicely played. Dimuth Karunaratne has found his rhythm. Loopy ball, outside off. The ball turns in a bit. Dimuth Karunaratne caresses it through extra cover and bags a boundary. Also, 100 up for Sri Lanka.
On off, Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out watchfully.
Rahkeem Cornwall (11-3-25-0) comes in from the opposite end now.

A length ball, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it towards mid off. The fielder was quick to get to the ball. Dimuth Karunaratne still waiting for that single to get to 50.
On a length, outside off, Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and defends it towards point.
Full-length ball, outside off, Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it to covers with soft hands.
A length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders his arms and lets it go to the keeper.

Quicker, full and on off. Nissanka remains solid in his defence.

Tossed up, around off. Nissanka blocks it out solidly.
On the pads, Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it towards mid-wicket for a single.
On off, Dimuth Karunaratne pushes it towards mid on.
Jomel Warrican to continue with his off-spin.
Full, around middle and leg. Dimuth Karunaratne tucks it towards mid-wicket for a single.

On middle and leg, nudged onto the leg side by Karunaratne.
Full and straight, Karunaratne flicks it straight to short mid-wicket.
On off and pushed back to the bowler.
Slightly fuller, outside off. Karunaratne edges it down towards short third man for a single.
On middle and Karunaratne pats it back to the bowler.
Around the off stump and dabbed down towards silly point.

Some width on offer this time from Rahkeem Cornwall. Pathum Nissanka rocks back and cuts it through cover-point. The fielder gives chase but the batters are able to come back for the third. Good running yet again.
On off and defended on the off side.
A touch shorter, around off and Karunaratne mistimes it towards cover-point for one.
Rahkeem Cornwall (9-3-19-0) is back into the attack. He replaces Roston Chase.
Slightly shorter and on middle and leg. Nissanka goes on the back foot and works it through mid-wicket for a couple of runs.
Warrican holds this one back a bit and bowls it on middle. Nissanka stays solid in defense.
Another quicker delivery, full and on off. Nissanka plays it towards cover.
This one skids through. Fired in on middle stump and Nissanka almost gets done by it.
On a length, around middle and Nissanka keeps it down on the leg side.
On middle, Karunaratne uses his feet to push it towards mid-wicket for a quick single. Good running.
Slowed up, around the off stump and Nissanka just defends it out. It is looking comfortable for the Lankan openers out there in the middle.
Full and on off, driven towards mid off.
FOUR! Poor delivery from Roston Chase. This is way down the leg side, Pathum Nissanka gets on his knees and puts it away behind square on the leg side for a boundary.
Looped up, on off and blocked out by Nissanka.
Down the leg side, Nissanka gets a tickle on it but Jason Holder makes a good stop at short fine leg.
Shorter delivery, around off and this one turns away from Karunaratne. He rocks back and mistimes the punch towards extra cover for a single.
This is pushed through a bit quicker and on off stump. Nissanka defends it with soft hands towards the gully region.
Fuller one, around off and caressed to cover.
On off and worked towards the cover region.

FOUR! Just over! Flighted delivery, outside off. Pathum Nissanka looks to be aggressive and hence comes down the track as he looks to lift it over mid on. The ball goes aerially off the toe end of the bat and just over the fielder at mid on for a boundary.
Flatter delivery, on off and punches back off the back foot.
Angled in on middle stump. Nissanka stays solid in defense.
Flatter delivery, on middle and this is pushed back to the bowler by Karunaratne.
Loopy ball, around off and pushed towards the cover region.
Short and wide, Karunaratne will feel he missed out on that one as he cuts it straight to point.
FOUR! Lack of timing on this occasion from Karunaratne but good enough to get a boundary. Tossed up, around off and Karunaratne just skips down the track and manages to beat the fielder at mid off.
On off and kept out on the off side by Karunaratne.
Nicely flighted, outside off. Karunaratne drives it with the spin but straight to cover.
Nicely bowled. Warrican slows it up a bit and bowls it on middle stump. Pathum Nissanka defends it off the front foot.
Fired in on middle stump, Karunaratne drives it down to long on for a run.
FOUR BYES! What happened here? Jomel Warrican bowls this one on a length, outside the off stump and the ball turns in a mile. The ball misses everything and goes past the keeper and into the fence.
Update - Jeremy Solozano is in a stable state at the moment after being taken to the hospital. The results of the scan came back as negative. It is not serious anymore. Thank god for that.
Tossed up delivery and pushed towards mid on.
Warrican drifts onto the pads but Karunaratne can't get it away as the ball goes off the pads and towards short leg.
On middle and flicked straight to short mid on.
Who will bowl from the other end? Jomel Warrican it is.
Tossed up, on middle. Karunaratne skips down the track and works it to the right of mid on for a quick single.
On off and firmly punched towards mid off.
Flighted ball, Karunaratne looks to use his feet but miscues it back to the bowler.
This is slowed up a bit and bowled on middle. Karunaratne defends it back to the bowler.
Flighted delivery, on off stump. Karunaratne defends it out with ease.
Chase starts with a full ball, on off stump. Karunaratne keeps it out on the off side.

The second session is set to begin. The umpire walk out to the middle first. They are followed by the West Indies players. Pathum Nissanka and Dimuth Karunaratne come out to continue the attack with the blade. Roston Chase to start with the ball.
... DAY 1, SESSION 2 ...

A pretty equal first session, but Sri Lanka will be the happier side. They would hope their batters are in the right frame of mind now and could grow into the innings. West Indies will hope to stick to their plans and draw the first blood. Another interesting session awaits, do join us in a short while.

A great bowling show by West Indies. All the bowlers were on song. Gabriel and Holder probed good lines and lengths. Cornwall and Warrican came in later and continued the same. They troubled the batters a bit more than the pacers. Chase was also able to turn the ball and created opportunities but it just did not go their way. West Indies lost two reviews as well in this session. They will hope to come back and attack the same way and keep the batters in check. Also, an horrific incident took place in the session and the debutant, Jeremy Solozano, was stretched off and taken to the hospital after taking a blow on his helmet. Hope he is all fine and we wish him a speedy recovery.

Sri Lankan off to a stable start! Nissanka and Karunaratne found it difficult to negotiate with the bowlers. They were off to a sedate start, as they were restricted to free their arms. Nissanka looked vulnerable against the ball shaping in off the pacers, while Karunarate, was struggling to take on the spin of Cornwall. He got a lifeline with a dropped catch. Since then, both the batters have looked to up the ante, they got a couple of boundaries. In the final 30 mins of the first session, the batters were kept in control yet again with spinners from each end. But a good thing for Sri Lanka is that they still remain unscathed.

Sri Lanka got off to a cautious start here. They haven’t yet justified their decision to bat. West Indies made sure the batters earn their runs. They have kept knocking at the door throughout the session but still are in the hunt for the breakthrough.
Flatter delivery, on the stumps. Nissanka stays solid in defense. That is it for the first session as the umpires call for Lunch on Day 1.
On off and Nissanka puts out a stride forward to defend it on the off side.
NO BALL! Another peach of a delivery from Jomel Warrican. This one turns away from the right-hander after pitching on off stump yet again. Warrican however, overstepped and a no ball is called.
Tossed up, on middle. Nissanka steps out but can't get it through mid off.

Beauty! This one gripped and beat the batter all ends up. Warrican bowls it on off stump and the ball turns away sharply after pitching and there's a bit of an extra bounce as well. Nissanka has no answer for that one.
On middle and Karunaratne brings out the on drive as he gets it to long on for a single.
Around off stump and Karunaratne keeps it out.
Chase drags it down again, on leg stump. Pathum Nissanka misses out on a freebie as he pulls it straight to short fine leg. End of a maiden over by Roston Chase.
Flighted ball, on middle and nudged away on the leg side by Nissanka this time.
Tossed up delivery, on the stumps and kept out by Nissanka.
On middle and leg, flicked away on the leg side by Nissanka.

Review! Kraigg Brathwaite takes a review for caught behind. The UltraEdge shows a flat-line as the ball passes the bat. Another review goes in vain for West Indies. The Ball Tracker comes in to check the lbw. The impact is way outside the line. The on-field decision of not out stays.

NOT OUT! Roston Chase bowls this one beautifully on a nagging length outside off. Pathum Nissanka doesn't know whether to come forward or rock back. Nissanka gets caught on the crease a bit as the ball just goes past the outside edge. UltraEdge shows that there's no bat involved and hence the original decision stays.
Looped up, outside off and defended on the off side.
Warrican drifts on the pads and Karunaratne brings out the sweep shot. Karunaratne gets it through fine leg as the fielder gives chase. The batters come back for the second with ease.
Nicely bowled! Around off and turning back in a bit. Karunaratne looks to run it down towards third man but edges it down towards the keeper.
Tossed up, outside off and Karunaratne flicks it to short mid-wicket.
On middle and kept out by Karunaratne.
Slightly shorter, around off. Pathum Nissanka punches it off the back foot down to long off for a single.
On middle and blocked out by Nissanka.

Almost drags on, does Karunaratne. Slowed up, around the off stump. Karunaratne looks to cut but the ball just doesn't come on and he ends up getting a bottom edge which does not go on to hit the stumps, luckily for him.
Short and wide, Karunaratne can't get it through the off side field.

Oh dear! The short leg fielder, Jeremy Solozano, gets hit on the helmet who was placed at the short leg. He goes down on the field. The medic is out with a stretcher to take the injured man out, just to be in line with the protocol. Thank god for the helmet. It was surely a nasty blow. The main concern here is that Solozano hasn't moved, this is probably due to the shock from the blow. He is now being stretchered off and rightly so. It's not a pretty sight but Solozano's condition is the priority right now and we just hope it's nothing serious.

That looked nasty! Chase drags it down and Dimuth Karunaratne rocks back to pull. He pulls it really hard and straight into the helmet of short leg, Jeremy Solozano. The debutant gets hit from close range and everyone seems to be worried. The stretcher is even out, we hope Solozano is fine.
On middle, Nissanka dances down the track and pushes it to wide long on for a single.
Flighted ball, around off stump and drifting in. Nissanka punches it off the back foot back to the bowler.
Darted around the off stump area. Nissanka defends it off the back foot.
Roston Chase comes into the attack now.

Tossed up, around leg. Dimuth Karunaratne makes room and looks to push it to the off side. The ball takes the inside edge and goes towards square leg. The batters take two runs. Dimuth Karunaratne gets lucky again. West Indies are consistently knocking on the door here, but are unable to find the breakthrough.
Tossed up, on off, Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out solidly.
On off, Dimuth Karunaratne helps it towards mid on.

After a lot of thought, Kraigg Brathwaite decides to review the LBW decision. UltraEdge shows that there's no bat involved and Ball Tracking shows that the impact was outside the line of off stump. The original decision of NOT OUT stays and the Windies lose a review as well.

NOT OUT! Poor shot selection by Dimuth Karunaratne. It could've been the breakthrough West Indies were looking for. Floated, full, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne comes across and looks to reverse-hit it but misses it completely. The ball goes through and hits the pads. Then it rolls out of the back foot and scoots past the leg pole. Dimuth Karunaratne is unaware off the ball and he turns back in panic to help the ball past the stumps. Meanwhile, Jomel Warrican appeals for an lbw and the umpire is unmoved. Kraigg Brathwaite decides to take it upstairs. The UltraEdge shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracker shows the impact is outside the line and the on-field decision stands.
Tossed up, full and around off. The ball spins in a bit. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it on to the pitch.
Flighted, full and around middle. Karunaratne comes forward and flicks it to mid-wicket.
Floated, full and on off. Nissanka defends it out watchfully.
Short and around off. Nissanka goes back and punches it through covers for another brace.
Short and outside off. Nissanka stays back and cuts it through point. The batters collect two runs. This also brings up 50 runs for the hosts.
Slower through the air, a bit of flight. Nissanka prods as he looks to defend it out but misses.
Flatter, around middle and leg. Nissanka tucks it to the leg side.
Floated, on off. Nissanka defends it out watchfully.
Full and on off. Karunaratne comes forward and punches it towards long on. But does not run to the other end this time.
Tossed up, on off. Nissanka hits it towards long on and grabs a single.
Full and on off. Nissanka defends it out watchfully.
Nice turn on this one! Looped up, full and on middle. The ball spins away. Nissanka defends it off the outer half towards cover. If the blade was missed, the stumps would've castled without a doubt.
Floated, full and on the pads. Nissanka tucks it to the leg side.
Tossed up, full and on off. Nissanka pushes it to cover.
Slightly shorter, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne goes on the back foot and plays it towards cover-point.
Tossed up delivery, Karunaratne steps out and pushes it to mid on.
Tossed up, around off and played off the back foot by Karunaratne.
This time it's sliding down the leg side and Dimuth Karunaratne just gets a tickle on it. The backward square leg fielder chases as the batters come back for a brace.
Fuller one, on middle and leg. Karunaratne keeps it out on the leg side.
On off and pushed towards cover.
Slightly shorter and on the pads. Pathum Nissanka rocks back and flicks it behind square on the leg side for a couple of runs.
On off and watchfully kept out by Nissanka this time.
Peach! Warrican bowls this one on a length, around off stump. The ball grips after pitching and turns away sharply from the right-hander. Pathum Nissanka is left bamboozled by that delivery.
Fuller delivery, on middle and Karunaratne steps out yet again. Karunaratne drives it down to long on for a single.
On middle, Karunaratne steps out and plays it back to the bowler.
Jomel Warrican comes into the attack now. He replaces Kyle Mayers.
Darted in, on middle and leg. Karunaratne drives it to short mid-wicket.
Nicely flighted yet again. Nissanka yet again looks to put out the stride and defnd but there's a bit of extra bounce and Nissanka gets an inside edge onto the pads.
Flighted ball, on off and Nissanka puts out a stride looking to defend. The ball goes off the pads towards short leg.
Tossed up delivery, on middle and driven straight to mid on.
Flatter again, on middle and pushing the batter on the back foot. Nissanka defends it back to the bowler.
On middle and worked towards mid-wicket.
Flatter delivery, outside off. Nissanka defends it off the back foot.
A length ball, just outside off stump and Karunaratne pushes it towards short cover.
Pitched up, on off and pushed to mid off.
Length again, outside off and cut away straight to point.

FOUR! Well picked up by Dimuth Karunaratne, who seems to be looking to up the ante now. Short ball, around off, nicely sat up for the batter. Dimuth Karunaratne pulls it aerially and the ball races away into the mid-wicket fence.
A length ball, angled into middle and leg. Dimuth Karunaratne plays it towards mid on.
Kyle Mayers comes into the attack now. He replaces Jason Holder.
Mayers starts from around the wicket and angles it in on middle stump. Dimuth Karunaratne stays solid in defense.
Slower this time and on a length, Nissanka plays it off the back foot towards mid-wicket.
Nicely flighted, on off and Nissanka pats it back to the bowler.
On the pads, flicked behind square on the leg side for a single.
Fired in at the pads. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to defend but misses and the ball loops up after hitting the pads and the square leg fielder pouches it.
On middle and leg, nudged towards square leg.
FOUR! A boundary after ages for the hosts. Rahkeem Cornwall just drags it down on middle stump. Dimuth Karunaratne rocks back and flicks it through the mid-wicket region for a boundary.
Angled into the pads this time, Nissanka manages to keep it out towards mid-wicket. Jason Holder has now bolwed three maidens on the trot.
Slightly fuller and outside off. Nissanka presents a dead bat at it.
On off this time and defended out on the off side.
Holder is probing around off and holding the length back a bit. Good-length ball, around off and played towards point.
Good-length ball, on off and Nissanka keeps it down towards point.
Back of a length, around off. Pathum Nissanka punches it off the back foot to cover.
Flighted ball, on off. Pathum Nissanka wrists it to deep square leg for a single.
On off and played towards point by Nissanka.
Dimuth Karunaratne finally gets off strike with the single. On middle and leg, flicked towards mid-wicket for a quick single.
A slider on the pads and flicked to square leg.
Fuller in length and punched nicely to mid off.
Tossed up, around off and Dimuth Karunaratne defends it towards cover.

Gabriel, Cornwall and Holder have done well with the ball and aren't letting the batters to score freely. Although, they only got a single opportunity to get a breakhrough but it was dropped in the slips. Sri Lanka would hope their batters remain unscathed till the next break. While the West Indies will look to snare a couple wickets.

Good-length ball, around the off stump. Pathum Nissanka hops and awkwardly keeps it down towards the gully region. Yet another maiden for Jason Holder and the Lankans openers just can't find an escape.
Back of a length, on off and Nissanka blocks it out.
On middle again and Nissanka keeps it out on the leg side.
Full and straight, driven nicely straight to mid on.

Dropped! After being tied down for long, Dimuth Karunaratne finally gives West Indies an opportunity but it's been squandered. Flighted ball, on off and turning away a bit. Full, on middle. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it back to the bowler.
Uppish but safe! Pushed through a bit quicker, on off stump. Dimuth Karunaratne is early in his cover drive but the ball lands well short of the cover fielder.
Flighted ball, on off and kept out by Dimuth Karunaratne.
Nicely tossed up, around middle and just drifting in. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to defend but gets an inside edge onto the back pad.
End of a really probing over from Jason Holder. Pitched up, outside off and caressed towards cover-point. Holder bowls his first maiden over of the day as well.
Shortish ball, outside off. Nissanka manages to keep it down towards the slip cordon.
This one came back in a long way. Length ball, on off and nips back in sharply as Nissanka gets squared up and gets hit in the ribcage area.
Peach! Holder pitches it up a bit, just outside off. The ball holds it's line this time and whizzes past the outside edge of Nissanka's willow.
A touch short and wide, Nissanka dabs it down towards point.
Back of a length, around off and this one nips back in sharply. It's been an area of vulnerability for Pathum Nissanka as once again he misses the ball and gets hit high on the pads.
Loopy ball, around middle and leg. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out watchfully.
On off, Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it out watchfully.

CLOSE! Nicely bowled by Rahkeem Cornwall. Full, on the pads, the ball turns in a bit. Dimuth Karunaratne is beaten with the turn and the lack of bounce. He gets hit on the pads. Rahkeem Cornwall puts in an appeal but the umpire is unmoved. Going down leg.
Flatter and outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne goes back and cuts it towards point.
Full, around middle and off. Dimuth Karunaratne gets his bat low in time and defends it out.
Floated, around middle and leg. The ball gets some extra bounce. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to flick it away but misses. He gets hit on the pads, but no trouble there.
On a length, around off. Nissanka prods and defends it to cover. A great over by Holder.
A length ball, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne comes across and nudges it to square leg for a single.
Back of a length, outside off, the ball angles across the left-hander. Dimuth Karunaratne does not chase it.
Good length, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays back and taps it towards point.
Full length, on the pads. Nissanka tucks it towards mid-wicket and gets a single.
A dot to start with! A length ball, around middle. Nissanka covers the stumps and defends it to the leg side.
Jason Holder (2-0-7-0) comes back into the attack.
Loopy ball, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne prods and defends it out watchfully.
Floated, full and on middle. Nissanka comes forward and pushes it towards long on for a single.
On off, pushed out but Nissanka.
Flighted, full and on off. Nissanka pushes it towards mid off.
Full and on the pads, Dimuth Karunaratne glances it down to fine leg. The batters pick three runs easily.

Nicely played by Pathum Nissanka. Good-length ball, on top of off. Nissanka punches it through cover-point off the back foot. The batters pick two runs with ease.

Nicely bowled! Gabriel is all over Nissanka. A length ball, on off. Nissanka gets an inside edge, onto the pads and the ball scoots past the leg pole. Although, not much trouble as the umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps.
Back of a length, around middle and off. The ball nips in off the pitch. Nissanka looks to defend it out but misses. He gets hit on the ribs. Nissanka is not liking this encounter with Gabriel.
Good-length ball, around off. Nissanka blocks it out off the front foot.
Tossed up, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne blocks it out.
Flighted, full and on off. Dimuth Karunaratne works it to cover but finds the fielder.
Full and on off, Karunaratne pushes it out.
BEAUTY! Looped up, full and outside off. The ball grips and turns off the pitch. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to defend it out but misses.

Loopy ball, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne taps it to point.
Here comes the first change. We are going to see spin for the first time today as Rahkeem Cornwall is brought into the attack.
Length ball, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it to cover and takes a single.

A single now! Nissanka gets himself out of the spotlight. Short ball, outside off. Nissanka hangs back and cuts it towards backward point. The fielder dives to his right and makes a half stop. They take one.

Pathum Nissanka gets hit on the gloves as he tries to defend the short ball. He seems to have hurt his fingers and is in a bit of pain. The physio is out and is giving treatment to Nissanka. Everything seems to be fine now and play can resume. Seeing the extra bounce from the previous delivery, Kraigg Brathwaite puts a short-leg in place.

Back of a length, on the bodyline. Nissanka hops and looks to tuck it away but misses. The ball gets an extra bounce, which makes it difficult for Nissanka to play at. He gets hit on his bottom hand, as it comes off the bat. The ball goes towards third man, but Nissanka is unaware and he turns 360 to know the whereabouts of the ball.

Length ball, around off. Nissanka stays back and defends it to point.

An excellent delivery to end the over. A length ball, outside off. The ball shapes away a bit. Dimuth Karunaratne looks to defend it out but misses. The ball whistles past the outside edge and into the keeper's mitts.
FOUR! Nicely played! Overpitched, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne leans in and drives it past mid off. The ball races away to the fence. He gets his first boundary of the innings.
Good running! A length ball, on the pads, Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it through square leg. The batters run two with ease.
A length ball, around off. The ball does not bounce much off the pitch this time. Dimuth Karunaratne gets his blade down and defends it out watchfully.
Back of a length, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne stays inside the creas and defends it back to the bowler.
Good-length ball, outside off, going across the left-hander. Dimuth Karunaratne leaves it alone.
Dimuth Karunaratne finally gets off the mark. A length ball, on the pads, Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it to square leg and gets a single.
NO BALL! Fuller, on off. Nissanka pushes it through covers and gets a single. The umpire signals a no ball, as the bowler oversteps.
SWING AND A MISS! Beaten all ends up! Gabriel serves a length ball, outside off, Nissanka looks to go for the booming drive but misses it completely. The ball zips past the outside edge.

Back of a length, on off. Nissanka stays inside the crease and taps it towards point.
Length ball, outside off, left alone.
Length ball, on the fourth stump line. Nissanka pushes it towards point off the front foot.

Holder serves a full-length delivery, around middle and leg. Dimuth Karunaratne gets his blade down and defends it to the leg side. Just a single off it. A great over by Holder. Dimuth Karunaratne yet to get off the mark.

Good-length ball, outside off. Dimuth Karunaratne shoulders his arms and lets it go to the keeper.
Good-length ball, around off. Dimuth Karunaratne defends it out watchfully.
Length ball, around middle and leg. Nissanka tucks it to mid-wicket and takes off for a single.
Back of a length, on off. Holder gets some deviation off the surface. Nissanka stays back and defends it back to the bowler.
Who will bowl from the other end? It's going to be Jason Holder.
LEG BYE! A length ball, on the pads. Nissanka looks to flick it away but misses. The ball clips the pads and goes to the leg side. The batters collect a leg bye.

FOUR! Pathum Nissanka and Sri Lanka are up and running. He finds the gap beautifully. A full-length ball, on off. Pathum Nissanka opens the face of the bat. The ball goes through the slip cordon and into the boundary at third man.
Length ball, outside off. Nissanka prods and shoulders his arms.
Much better from Gabriel. Good-length ball, outside off. The ball gets an extra bounce off the surface. Nissanka lets it sail past him and into the keeper's mitts.
Gabriel is finding it difficult to maintain his line. He bowls another delivery, down leg. Nissanka does not chase it.

We are ready for play! The umpires are in the middle along with the West Indies players. Dimuth Karunaratne and Pathum Nissanka are the openers for Sri Lanka. Shannon Gabriel has been handed the new ball as we can also see the Windies players taking the knee to show their support for the 'Black Lives Matter' movement.

Pitch Report - Aamer Sohail is pitchside. He says that Galle's pitch is a typical one and the spinners will play an important role. There is a bit of moisture but that will be baked down by the sun and it's going to be tough for the batters. The toss will play a big role as well.
We are set to get underway. Both the teams stride out to the middle for the national anthems. It will be West Indies' anthem first followed by the one of Sri Lanka.
Kraigg Brathwaite, the West Indies captain, is up for a chat. He says, he would have opted to bat first as well. Mentions, they have had enough practice sessions under their belly away from home.

Dimuth Karunaratne, the skipper of Sri Lanka, says that they will have a bat first. He says that the wicket is pretty good and they know how the track is going to play out, so looking to put a good total on the board. He adds that they have been playing with three spinners and have part-timers as well, so it's on the batters to put on a good total. Mentions that they have been practicing really hard the last couple of days.

West Indies (Playing XI) - Kraigg Brathwaite (C), Jermaine Blackwood, Jeremy Solozano, Nkrumah Bonner, Roston Chase, Kyle Mayers, Jason Holder, Joshua Da Silva (WK), Rahkeem Cornwall, Jomel Warrican, Shannon Gabriel.

Sri Lanka (Playing XI) - Dimuth Karunaratne (C), Pathum Nissanka, Oshada Fernando, Dhananjaya de Silva, Angelo Mathews, Dinesh Chandimal (WK), Ramesh Mendis, Suranga Lakmal, Dushmantha Chameera, Lasith Embuldeniya, Praveen Jayawickrama.
TOSS - Up goes the coin and it lands in favour of Sri Lanka. They have opted to BAT first.

Sri Lanka went into the 2021 T20 World Cup with few expectations and even though it was their least successful campaign, the young Lankan Lions showed good promise and gathered a whole lot of praise for their efforts. The star of their campaign, Charith Asalanka got his maiden call-up for a Test series and will be looking to make his debut today. The hosts also have experience in their ranks for the longest format of the game. During the last WTC cycle, Sri Lanka couldn't muster any points and they will be desperate to change that against a team they have a great record at home.

West Indies probably had their worst ever T20 World Cup campaign most recently and will now be looking to leave behind the blemishes of the shortest format of the game. Touring Sri Lanka hasn't been much fruitful for the Windies, specially when it comes to Test cricket. One advantage which West Indies do have is that they have some points on the borad in the ICC World Test Championship table, with that historic victory against Pakistan in a home Test match. Kraigg Brathwaite will be looking to marshall his troops and lead them to another such victory against the Islanders.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 1 of the first Test match between Sri Lanka and West Indies. The two-match Test series is to be played at Galle and both teams will be looking to maximize this opportunity to get some valuable points on the board for the ICC World Test Championship. When these two sides meet in the longest format of the game, it's Sri Lanka who have the upper hand and the conditions will be in their favour too. There is some light rain to be expected in Galle as well. Can West Indies spring a surprise and win a first away series against the Islanders in almost three decades? Or will the hosts make full use of the spin friendly conditions? We'll find out over the course of the next five days. Toss and team news in a bit.
... Day 1, Session 1 ...
The game set to begin. West Indies players stride out to the middle. Followed by Dimuth Karunaratne and Pathum Nissanka walk out to bat for Sri Lanka. Rahkeem Cornwall to start with the ball.

Right then, Sri Lanka will come out to bat with a lead of 156 runs. The West Indies need to pick some early wickets and make sure the batters don’t take the game away from them. With the current climate conditions, the bowlers will get some purchase off the pitch. A great session of play awaits do join us in short while.

Sri Lanka have been exceptional with both the blade and the ball. They put up a total of 386 in the first innings. Thanks to an impressive knock by their skipper, Dimuth Karunaratne, he was well supported by the batter from the other end. As they came out to bowl, it was their spinners bowled in tandem in the middle and caused a lot of problem to the opposition batters. Later, Ramesh Mendis came into the attack and picked up three wickets in quick succession to lead West Indies near the exit door. Praveen Jayawickrama was the pick of the bowlers with a four-wicket haul. Mendis bagged three wickets. While rest of the bowlers took a wicket each except Dushmantha Chameera.A job well done by the Sri Lankan bowlers.

West Indies tail order could not hang around for a longer period of time with just one wicket in hand. The top order could not get off to a solid start and it could’ve been gotten worse for the visitors but Cornwall, Mayers, Holder and Silva made sure to avoid the follow-on. Joshua Da Silva was the last remaining known batter in the middle at the start of Day 4. He could not handle the pressure alone, he tried to keep Gabriel off the strike for the most part of the over, but Gabriel could not survive an arm-ball of Jayawickrama.

Right. So just the 35 balls needed for Sri Lanka this morning to end the West Indian innings. Time is more of an important factor for them, as they need to dictate terms in the game, with time lost. Day 4 of the Test game, started off on a bad note with the rain gods smiling upon us. There was a delay to the start. And once the players came back on to resume play, Sri Lanka did not take much time to scalp the last wicket. Sri Lanka still have a lead of 156 runs under their sleeves.

Day 3 started off brightly with the West Indies lower order staging a remarkable comeback. The visitors went from hoping to avoid follow-on to adding 111 runs in the day with the loss of just three wickets. Sri Lanka spinners toiled hard early in the morning but did get the two set batsmen, Holder and Mayers out in quick succession. However, Rahkeem Cornwall and Joshua Da Silva did not let the hosts a get a grip on proceedings, with Cornwall hitting the spinners to all ends of the ground. In the second session, Cornwall did get out but then rain played spoilsport. Rain has been pouring all throughout the afternoon and after a couple of tries to get some play in, the umpires decided to call it a day. Things now get interesting, as we still have two more days to go and if the weather permits, this match can still end with a result. Sri Lanka will carry over their sizeable lead of 162 runs into Day 4 with just one more wicket to get.

Right then, another riveting session of Test cricket has flown by where a total of 102 runs were scored from 33 overs and just 2 wickets fell. The game is still in the hands of the hosts but the visitors are making some significant progress with the bat. If they bat for an hour more, who knows what might happen later in this match. Join us soon for the second session as it promises to be mouth-watering.

Sri Lanka will be pleased in the end with the lead they still hold but it wasn't as easy as they expected this morning. It was all spin from the hosts as the pace bowlers just bowled two overs at the backend of the session. The surface was helping the spinners but they just couldn't find the right lengths consistently. The pair of Holder and Mayers attacked them early on but once they got rid of them, one would expect them to clean up the tail. This wasn't to be as Rahkeem Cornwall launched a counter attack which hurt the hosts and they don't have as big a lead. Sri Lanka will now be looking to come out guns blazing after Lunch and make sure they get rid of the remaining two wickets.

Resistance! Yes, it has been resistance of quite some quality, first from the overnight batters, Kyle Mayers and Jason Holder and then from Rahkeem Cornwall and Joshua Da Silva. The overnight batters not only survived the spinners but even countered with some classy shots. The pair added 50 runs this morning and 63 overall for the 7th wicket but then Mayers fell and Holder followed him to the pavilion soon after. This broke the Windies' backbone but Joshua Da Silva and Rahkeem Cornwall too batted well and made sure that the visitors avoided the follow on. They have already added 40 runs and the big man, Cornwall has taken a liking to the Lankan spinners as he hit some lusty blows.

Death by spin, is the term to be used for this Test match so far. 16 of the 18 wickets to fall so far have been taken by spinners and the visitors have really been mostly undone by the Lankan spinners. The first session on Day 3 has moved at a rate of knots and has been pretty even but in the end the visitors have just frustrated the hosts by extending their stay at the crease.

Lasith Embuldeniya is down for a quick chat. He says that they want to get Windies out as soon as possible and they will think about follow on later. Adds ghat they wanted to score 400 but are happy with what they got. Tells that there is turn and bounce in this pitch and it will turn more as the game progresses. Says that he keeps things very simple and looks to turn the ball. Tells that he enjoys playing Test cricket and says that right from school cricket he has been playing longer format.

PITCH REPORT - Farvez Maharoof is pitchside. Aamer Sohail joins him and assesses that the pitch is turning and there's bounce on offer as well, making it even more difficult for the batters. He adds that there is a way to counter this and that is to stay positive and use their feet.

West Indies bowled well on Day 2 and managed to bowl out the hosts under 400. They did get off to a good start with the bat as well when their openers Brathwaite and Blackwood were able to see off the new ball. But once the spinners came on, they found it hard to cope with the turn and bounce and perished. Wickets kept tumbling as there was no respite from the Lankan spinners and the momentum shifted completely in Sri Lanka's favour. However, Kyle Mayers has come out with positive intent at no.7 and the visitors would hope that he goes on to get a big one for them. Jason Holder also has a great opportunity to show his worth with the bat and he would be keen to put on a show when his team needs him the most. We are in for an intriguing day of Test cricket so do not go anywhere as the action on Day 3 will begin shortly.

Sri Lanka put up a decent first innings score but their pacers failed to make early inroads and the Windies openers managed to go into the Tea break unscathed. However, once the spinners got into their act, Sri Lanka never looked back and picked up wickets at regular intervals. Ramesh Mendis was introduced late in the day but he made an immediate impression and grabbed 3 wickets which sent the visitors on the back foot. Embuldeniya and Jayawickrama also bowled well and kept the batters in check. Fair to say, it was a day which was dominated by Sri Lanka who find themselves in the driver's seat now!

Hello and a very warm welcome to Day 3 of the first Test between Sri Lanka and West Indies. The game has moved at the rate of knots in the latter half of Day 2 and the visitors are in a spot of bother at 113/6, courtesy of some fine bowling by the Lankan spinners. The pitch has started to turn square and the Windies have a mountain to climb as they are trailing hy 273 runs with only 4 wickets in hand. They do bat deep but the overnight batters have their task cut out and must take Windies to safer shores. Having said that, rain is predicted to play spoilsport on Day 3 but we hope that the rain gods stay away and we get to see another scintillating day of Test cricket.
...Day 3, Session 1...

Right then! That is all we have from this day. Day 3 is usually considered the moving day of a Test match and West Indies would surely hope that Day 3 moves in their favour. But that seems very difficult as the pitch is offering more and more help to the spinners. The first job for West Indies is to make sure that they avoid the follow on. Do join us on 23rd November at 10 am Local (4:30 am GMT) for the third day's action. Till then, goodbye and take care!

It was a topsy-turvy day for West Indies. At first, they seemed helpless with the ball but staged a superb comeback, led by their spinners, Roston Chase and Jomel Warrican. The visitors managed to restrict the hosts to a total below what was expected at one time, thanks to a five-wicket haul from Roston Chase. West Indies had a decent start with the bat as both Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood saw the new ball through. It was when the spinners bowled in tandem that the Windies batters looked vulnerable. Apart from skipper Brathwaite, no one else put up much of a fight. Wickets kept on tumbling and the visitors find themselves reeling on 113 for 6 at the end of the second day. They still need 74 runs to avoid the follow on and it's going to be a tough ask for them on Day 3.

Sri Lanka had a set platform from Day 1 but as the second day progressed, they kept on losing their advantage with the bat. Only Dinesh Chandimal looked comfortable out in the middle as the hosts lost seven wickets inside two sessions and ended up putting 386 runs on the board when at one stage they looked to be on course for a score beyond 450. With the ball also they did not have the best of starts but as soon as they picked up the first wicket, their spinners got a grip on the match. Lasith Embuldeniya and Praveen Jayawickrama bowled well in tandem but after a while, the visitors got quite comfortable at the crease. Then Ramesh Mendis was brought in and he picked up 3 wickets in a flash, putting the Lankans on top of proceedings at the end of the second day.

What a riveting day of cricket we've had on Day 2! A total of 13 wickets fell in the day as the momentum kept on swinging either side and the contest between bat and ball was one to witness. In the end, the hosts will be the happier of the sides going into the third day as they take a huge lead of 273 runs into the next day, with West Indies only having four wickets remaining.

Fuller again, on off. Jermaine Blackwood leans into it and blocks it. Chameera sticks his left hand out and gathers the ball.
Short ball, on off. Jermaine Blackwood sways away from the line of the ball.
Drifting down the leg side. Kraigg Brathwaite works it to fine leg for an easy single.
Fuller ball, on off. Pushed back to the bowler with soft hands.
Back of a length, on off. Jermaine Blackwood clips it past mid-wicket for a single.

Length ball, right on the off pole. Kraigg Brathwaite presses forward and blocks it with soft hands.
Length ball, outside off. Left alone with ease.
Another short one and Kraigg Brathwaite ducks under this too.
Shorter ball, on off. Kraigg Brathwaite sits under it. The keeper dives to his left and collects it.
Fuller ball, lands on off and comes in with the angle. KB blocks it from the crease.
Length ball, on the pads. Worked past square leg for a single now.
Fired straight on the stumps. Kraigg Brathwaite offers the full face of the bat and blocks it.
Loopy ball, wider outside off. Left alone this time.
Well bowled and well left! Quicker and just outside off. KB thinks of blocking it but leaves it at the last moment.
Loopy ball, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite gets forward to block it.
Tossed up, wide outside off. Left alone.
FOUR! Slapped! Shorter ball, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite slaps it hard. The man at point dives over it and it runs to the fence.
Fuller ball, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite leans into it and guides it past point. The fielder dives to his left and stops the ball. Still, the batters get a single.
Lakmal bowls it full, on off. A solid defence is offered by Kraigg Brathwaite.
On a length, wide enough for Kraigg Brathwaite to leave it with ease.
Back of a length, quite wide outside off. KB does not chase this one.
Fired on the pads. Kraigg Brathwaite taps it to mid-wicket.
Fuller ball, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite leans into it and taps it to covers.
Suranga Lakmal (3-1-4-0) comes to bowl.
Another one outside off and left alone. An entertaining first over after Tea.
Loopy ball, wide outside off. Left alone.
SIX! Top shot! Tossed up, on off. Jermaine Blackwood heaves it straight down the ground for a maximum.

Beaten! Tossed up, just outside off. Blackwood looks to block but the ball turns sharply and goes past the bat. Chandimal gathers it and goes up in appeal but there is no bat on that. Just some vicious turn.
FOUR! Quality stroke! Darted on the pads by Lasith Embuldeniya. Jermaine Blackwood gets low and sweeps it hard to the square leg fence.
Tossed up, on off. Bit of turn on it. Blackwood looks to defend but gets the inside edge on the pads.
We are back for the last session on Day 2! The players stride out to the middle. Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood take the crease. Lasith Embuldeniya to start the final session.
... Day 2, Session 3 ...

Sri Lanka have started well with the ball but they would be kicking themselves as they did not opt for a review when Jermaine Blackwood was trapped in front by Dushmantha Chameera. The spinners were introduced early and they troubled the Windies' opening batters right from the word go. Dimuth Karunaratne would hope that his spinners get some early breakthroughs post the Tea interval and put the visitors on the back foot. Another intriguing session of Test cricket awaits us which begins shortly!

West Indies have managed to go into the Tea break unscathed and that would ease some nerves in their dressing room. However, Jermaine Blackwood would consider himself very lucky as he was given a life by Sri Lanka when they decided to go against taking a review. Kraig Brathwaite looked good in the middle and he too got a life on the last ball before Tea when he reviewed his LBW decision. The ball has started to turn sharply and Windies have a steep task ahead of them.

NOT OUT! Kraigg Brathwaite survives on the final ball before tea! Tossed up, on middle and this one just slides on with the arm. Brathwaite looks to put out a stride and defend but misses and gets hit on the pads. Praveen Jayawickrama appeals and the umpire eventually raises his finger. Brathwaite reviews and Ball tracking confirms that the ball was sliding down the leg side. The umpire changes his decision and also signals for the Tea break. What a gripping session it has been!
Review time! Kraigg Brathwaite has opted for a review after being adjudged LBW by the umpire. The Sri Lankans are celebrating as they look really confident.
A touch shorter, on off. Brathwaite defends it off the back foot.
Tossed up, on off and Blackwood strides out looking to defend. The ball takes the outside edge and goes past first slip. They get a single.
That was a peach of a delivery! Nicely flighted, around the off stump. The ball grips and turns away sharply, leaving the batter bamboozled.
Floated up, on middle and Blackwood stays solid in defense.
Tossed up, around off and Blackwood defends it back to the bowler.
Praveen Jayawickrama comes to bowl now.
On middle again and kept out on the leg side.
Slowed up, on middle and watchfully defended out by Brathwaite.
Beautifully flighted, on middle and drawing the batter forward. Brathwaite blocks it out.
Tossed up, around off and kept out on the off side.
Poor second delivery from Lasith Embuldeniya. Full toss, on middle and Brathwaite misses out as he hits it straight into the wrist of the fielder at short leg.
Spin straightaway for Lasith Embuldeniya. Looped up, on middle and the ball grip and turns away sharply. Brathwaite plays it with soft hands but edges it just past the fielder at first slip.
Lasith Embuldeniya comes to bowl.
On top of off and kept out by Blackwood.
Lakmal goes fuller, on off and looking to bring the ball back in. Blackwood defends it off the front foot.
Back of a length, on off and pushing the batter on the back foot. Jermaine Blackwood remains solid in defense.
Full and straight, Blackwood punches it straight to mid on.
On middle and this is pushed towards mid-wicket.
A touch short and wide, Blackwood hangs back and cuts it through cover-point for a brace.
Length again, on middle and kept out on the off side.
Back of a length, around off and Brathwaite blocks it out.
Another spicy short ball. Brathwaite does well to duck under it.

LEG BYE! Oh, that looked really close! A length ball, angled in at middle and leg. Blackwood looks to flick but gets squared up and gets rapped on the pads. The hosts appeal but the umpire remains unmoved. The ball rolls towards backward point and they get a leg bye. The review isn't taken and maybe Sri Lanka just missed a trick here.
Well directed short ball from Dushmantha Chameera. Around off stump and at 142 kph. Blackwood sways away from the ball and hangs out his bat as well but misses the ball.
Good-length ball, outside off. Brathwaite hangs back and eases it to wide of cover-point for a single.
On a length, just outside off. Blackwood shoulders arms.
Lakmal pitches it up and bowls it outside off. Blackwood makes an assured leave.
Good-length ball, on off and this is punched towards the cover region.
Almost an action replay of the previous delivery. This time just the line was outside off.
Slightly shorter, around middle. Blackwood defends it off the back foot.
Blackwood is off the mark too! A length ball, angled in on middle and leg. Blackwood tucks it through mid-wicket and comes back for the second with ease.
FOUR! Width on offer and the Windies skipper gets off the mark in style. Short and wide, Brathwaite slaps it through backward point and picks up a boundary.
Back of a length, around middle and Brathwaite just manages to keep it out.
Full, around off and at 143 kph. Brathwaite punches it nicely but the fielder at short cover makes a really good diving stop.
Good-length ball, outside off and tapped straight to cover-point.
Chameera hits the length hard, around off. Brathwaite hops and taps it back onto the deck.

Who will bowl from the other end? Dushmantha Chameera it is.
A maiden to start proceedings! Around off and Brathwaite plays it with soft hands towards cover.
Right on the money from Lakmal. Again it's a probing line, around off and Brathwaite manages to keep it out on the off side.
In that channel outside off and Brathwaite just watchfully leaves it alone.
Length again, on off and defended back to the bowler by Brathwaite.
A slight bit of shape away from the right-hander. Around the off stump and moving away, Brathwaite let's it through to the keeper.
Lakmal starts off with a length ball on the pads. Kraigg Brathwaite tucks it towards mid-wicket from the middle of the bat.

The final session is set to begin. The Sri Lankan players stride out to the middle. They are followed by Kraigg Brathwaite and Jermaine Blackwood who walk out to open for West Indies. Lasith Embuldeniya to start with the new ball.
... DAY 4, SESSION 3 ...

Right then. West Indies have a stiff mountain to climb, as they come out to chase a target of 348 runs. Let us also keep in mind, the purchase off the deck for the spinners. With the bowling line-up that Sri Lanka possess they can run riots with the ball.  But did you forget the miracle that the Windies pulled out in Antigua? During the first Test match against the Islanders. They battled throughout the last day to squeeze out a result. Can they repeat their heroics yet again, but this time away from home and alongwith a tricky condition? We shall find out soon, as the final session is not far away.

West Indies got a good start, courtesy of Rahkeem Cornwall. Soon, Jomel Warrican snared a wicket as well. It is what they desired, pick early wickets and not let Sri Lanka score freely. Although the team excelled in the first objective, they rather lost their track achieving their second goal. The third wicket stand proved to be costly for the visitors. The West Indies players were chirpy on the field but all gone quiet once the pair stitched a 100-run stand. That’s when they started losing the edge. It was deep in the second session, when Cornwall struck again to get rid of Dimuth Karunaratne. Also, Jomel Warrican sent back a new batter in Dhananjaya de Silva. Later, Mathews and Chandimal hit a few lusty blows before the hosts decided to declare.

Early Tea has been called here on Day 4! SRI LANKA have finally declared, looks like Dimuth Karunaratne was waiting for a biggie, but on a serious note, the hosts certainly hold the upper hand in this game. It was their experienced pair of Dimuth Karunaratne and Angelo Mathews who made sure to swell the lead consistently. The former slipped out of his chance of scoring a ton in each innings. Although, Mathews scored a composed innings and smacked 69 runs not out. Mathews kept going till the end and had his foot on the gas in the end. They have set up a target of 348 runs.
SIX! THUMPED! A full ball, on middle. Angelo Mathews slog-sweeps it well over mid-wicket for a biggie. SRI LANKA DECLARE ON 191/4. THEY NOW LEAD BY 347 RUNS.
Full and on middle. Mathews tucks it to square leg.
Darted on the pads, this is flicked to square leg for a single.

Full and on off. Mathews works it to long off for a single.

A single now as this is eased to long off.
FOUR! Nicely played! Full and on leg. Dinesh Chandimal steps across and sweeps it towards fine leg for a boundary.
On leg, Chandimal defends it out watchfully.

Flighted, full and on middle. Angelo Mathews works it to long on for a single.

Full, on the pads. Chandimal tucks it to square leg for a single. He gets off the mark.
Full, on the pads. Mathews flicks it to mid-wicket for a single.
Full and down leg. Angelo Mathews sweeps and works it to short fine leg.

OUT! CAUGHT AND BOWLED! Dhananjaya de Silva's short stay comes to an end. Warrican gets his second wicket. The ball is doing its magic now. Jomel Warrican keeps his eyes on the ball and takes a sharp catch. Also, a wicket -maiden for Warrican.

Full and on off. Dhananjaya de Silva defends it to cover.

Jermaine Blackwood keeps his eyes on the ball and takes a simple catch. A huge breakthrough for West Indies.

Full and on middle. Dimuth Karunaratne flicks it through mid-wicket for a couple.

Floated, full and on off. Mathews pushes it through covers for a single.
DRINKS! Sri Lanka in a commanding position as they now lead by 310 runs. Will they declare after reaching the 350 mark or do they want more composure? Time will tell. Jomel Warrican to bowl now.
FIFTY up for Angelo Mathews! A composed knock played by him. On the pads, Angelo Mathews flicks it to square leg and gets off for a single.
Touch short, on off. Dimuth Karunaratne pulls it through mid on for a single.
On off, kept out solidly.

In the air...Safe! Tossed up, around off. The ball turns away. Dimuth Karunaratne gets low and looks to sweep it away. The ball takes the top edge and goes towards deep mid-wicket.
