The second session is set to begin. The West Indies players stride out to the middle. Followed by Angelo Mathews and Dimuth Karunaratne who walk out to bat for the hosts. Jason Holder to start with the ball.
... DAY 4, SESSION 2 ...

Rahkeem Cornwall bowled throughout the first session as he was turning the ball sharply and making things happen. He took one wicket but would have another one if they had taken that LBW review against Dimuth Karunaratne. From the other end, Jomel Warrican was used mostly as he too was rolling his fingers nicely. Too early to call for the result but West Indies will be pretty pleased with a draw and if they aspire for something bigger, wickets are a must and that too at a rapid pace. We have an interesting session coming up. Do join us in a while.

A session which was started late due to rain, the hosts still hold an upper hand going into the break as they now lead by 240 runs. Dimuth Karunaratne and Angelo Mathews have done well to pass this session but they would look to score with more pace if they want to win this match, keeping the conditions in mind. Pathum Nissanka and Oshada Fernando fell cheaply but since then, these two have done well to build a partnership.

Kraigg Brathwaite, the West Indies skipper says that Joshua and Bonner showed a commendable fight right from yesterday and as a batter, they should learn from it. He adds that the first innings is always important in Test matches and they were short there. He mentions that toss was crucial but as professional cricketers, they need to adapt. He applauded the bowlers for their show and praises Gabriel for the aggression he showed but adds that they were short in the batting department. He mentions that they need to learn from this game quickly and if they have to defend, then defend it with confidence.

Dimuth Karunaratne is the Man of the Match, he says that he was playing a long time, it was a good game for him. Says that they were a bit worried as they didn't play much Test cricket in between but he is proud of the players. Says that experienced players are helping young ones all the time. Tells that they do the job when they get the ball. Mentions that it was raining heavily so they went with two pacers but they will see the condition and the wicket before choosing the playing XI. Says that he needs to carry on the good role. He have some targets to achieve and will continue to help the team.

Earlier after opting to bat first, Dimuth Karunaratne showed his brilliance in the red-ball yet again as he scored an astonishing 147 runs. Dhananjaya de Silva, Pathum Nissanka and Dinesh Chandimal played wonderful cameos. Their brilliance was followed by the bowlers as they bundled out West Indies for 230. Sri Lanka extended their lead, thanks to yet another beautiful performance from their captain, Dimuth Karunaratne and their former captain, Angelo Mathews. After that, it was all spinners as they did the job. West Indies showed a good fight, things would have been different if their middle-order performed well but that isn't the case.

It was spin, spin and spin from Sri Lanka and why not when you are getting the reward. It was Lasith Embuldeniya and Ramesh Mendis who showed their magic skills and reduced West Indies for 18/6. The game was solely under the control of the hosts but unfortunately, they failed to break the 7th wicket partnership and it took the game bit away. They had to work hard for the wicket and the spinners were later awarded for their work. A five-fer for Ramesh Mendis and four-fer for Lasith Embuldeniya sealed the game.

West Indies showed good fight until the end. It looked like the visitors will be bundled out at the fag end of Day 4 after been 18/6 but since then, Bonner and Da Silva showed good spirit and turned the fortunes. Not all but enough for the game to resume on the last day. They continued to show their technical abilities and almost survived the first session without losing a wicket but Da Silva fell in the end. Nkrumah Bonner played more than 200 deliveries and he anchored until the end but Rahkeem Cornwall, Jomel Warrican and Shannon Gabriel failed to help him. Even luck was against them as it started raining just when Gabriel fell. A disappointing ending but a fighting show from West Indies and especially from Nkrumah Bonner.

Sri Lanka take the lead in this two-Test match series against West Indies by 1-0. It took much more time than we thought but credit to West Indies to stretch the innings. Sri Lanka would have been frustrated with the lack of wickets this morning. At least, that was seen from coach Mickey Arthur's frantic movements in the dressing room, not relaxing much. But this one wicket before Lunch would have revived their spirits. They have bowled beautifully, especially the spinners, but wickets have been hard to come by. And sometimes that happens. When the ball is turning too much, the bowlers tend to do a bit more than required and hence, struggle to get wickets.

West Indies began the day cautiously, with da Silva and Bonner playing it out sensibly. The deck was under covers, hence the ball did not quite spin as much as anticipated. Sri Lanka then resorted to seam bowling, especially to Bonner, from around the wicket. One believes that is where the hosts lost the ploy a little bit, not quite making use of the moisture on the wicket. Probably, fuller lengths would have been better. But the visitors rode that time out. There was some drama, an LBW review being turned down and a decision being overturned. But just when it seemed like luck was shining on West Indies, Lasith Embuldeniya struck, towards the end of the session, claiming Joshua Da Silva, breaking the mammoth stand of 100 in 268 balls.

Ahem, ahem! Half an hour? One hour? 90 minutes? Stand up all those of you, who felt that this game would go beyond the first session. Pat yourselves on your backs. And now, credit to West Indies. What a fine session of cricket. Yes, they are well down and out in this game, probably not far away from a defeat but still, they have fought hard. 73 runs in this session, in 35.3 overs. Slow, yes. But who is bothered about the run rate? Crucially, they lost just the one wicket and are still hanging in there.

Whoa! Almost another wicket for Sri Lanka, right at the stroke of Lunch! Everyone is smiling. Yes, literally. Dhananjaya de Silva is on his haunches, covering his smile. Or trying to. Embuldeniya takes his cap and smiles as well. Now, Dimuth Karunaratne is walking back with a smile on his face. Now, the camera pans onto the batsmen and aha... Rahkeem Cornwall has a gentle smile on his face. A really gentle smile for a big man. Oh my, even the umpire is smiling! Dear me, that was a close shave. A really close one. A full toss, on middle, should have been swatted away really. And Cornwall tried to. But he just could not get his bat down at the right time. To his near horror, he missed it, well almost. The ball curved in and luckily for him, took the under edge and hit him on the pads. That was heading straight onto the stumps and an LBW was on the cards, but for the under edge. A dramatic finish to the opening session on the final day!

Day 4 was solely dominated by the host. First, they stretched their lead by more than 350 runs and then the spin duo, Ramesh Mendis and Lasith Embuldeniya showed their magic as the visitors were unable to face them. They were 18/6 at one stage and it looked like the game will end in the third session itself but Joshua Da Silva and Nkrumah Bonner did well to steady the ship.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 5 of the first Test match between Sri Lanka and West Indies at Galle. The game is poised in the favour of Sri Lanka as they need just 4 wickets to win. For West Indies, it is a mountain to climb as they need 296 runs to win or even to manage a draw out of it.
...Day 5, Session 1…

Right then! The game is poised for an interesting last day and it will take some batting from West Indies to even get a draw out of it. Sri Lanka, on the other hand, will be itching to come out and finish the job. Day 5 will start at 0945 Local Time (0415 GMT) on 25th November. But our build up will begin well in advance. Do join us early. Till then, goodbye and take care!

What do we write about such an exceptional performance like this one? Sri Lanka spinners spun their web around the West Indies batters and strangled them. The conditions have favored the spinners and they ran riot with the ball. Ramesh Mendis started the proceedings and he went onto pick up a four-wicket haul. Lasith Embuldeniya was the other spinner who found success today. He bagged a couple of wickets. Praveen Jayawickrama looked to be a real threat but could not find any success, although one day remains for him to strike. Sri Lanka, need only 4 wickets to take a lead in this Test series and they would be eager to finish things quickly on the final day.

This was the worst ever start for West Indies in a Test match. That tells you everything how it has been for the visitors. They were 18/6 at one moment. No batter could counter well against the Lankan spin attack. No batter except Joshua Da Silva and Bonner could get into double digits. A horrifying sight for a West Indies fan. The pair of Da Silva and Bonner fought hard and made sure they do not lose any more wickets before stumps on Day 4. Although they have a huge task ahead of them if they are to squeeze a result out of a precarious position.

The Sri Lankan spinners have managed to take the game away from the visitors. The hosts have the game by the scruff of the neck. The batters kept looking for the turn while the bowlers remained persistent with the sliders and got rewards. Sri Lanka are right on top and will be the happier side at the end of Day 4 without any doubt.

Ful and on off, pushed to mid off.
Flatter and on middle. Nkrumah Bonner prods to defend. It takes the inside edge and rolls towards square leg for a single.
On off. Joshua Da Silva works it towards mid on.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva continues to stay inside the crease and defends it to point.
On off, Joshua Da Silva defends it out.
Floated up, on off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out watchfully.
Flatter, on the pads. Bonner defends it out off the outer half, as ball goes towards third man, They take one.
Touch short, around leg. Bonner looks to pull it away but misses and gets hit high on the pads. Pitching outside leg.
On off, Joshua Da Silva continues to remain solid in his defense.
Tossed up, on off. Joshua Da Silva defends it out.
On off, Da Silva blocks it out watchfully.
An umpire review now! The soft signal is not out. It looks like a bump ball as the ball hits the ground first and then the pads. Yes, the third umpire confirms the same.

NOT OUT! Full, around middle and leg. Joshua Da Silva looks to dig it out to the leg side. The ball deflects to the off side off the pads and the fielder at silly point turns and takes a good catch. The players appeal but the umpire is unmoved. Although, he refers to confirm. The soft signal is not out. The replays show that the ball has bounced before deflecting off the pads. The on-field decision stays.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva defends it with a straight bat.
Tossed up, on off. Joshua Da Silva stays back and pushes it out.
Loopy ball, around leg. The ball turns in. Bonner leaves it alone and the ball goes down leg.
Flatter and on off. Joshua Da Silva pushes it to point for a single.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva leans forward and pushes it back to the bowler.
A single now! Floated, around leg. Bonner goes back and tucks it to square leg for a single.
Full and on the pads. Bonner clips it to square leg.
Tossed up, on off. Nkrumah Bonner defends it solidly.
On off, Joshua Da Silva blocks it out watchfully.

Review time! Sri Lanka take a review for a caught behind. Joshua Da Silva tries to sweep but seems to miss it. Dinesh Chandimal behind the stick is optimistic with this one. UltraEdge shows it brushed the pads. Sri Lanka lose their review.

NOT OUT! Full and going down leg. Joshua Da Silva looks to sweep it away but misses. Dinesh Chandimal moves to his left and takes a good low catch. He is asking the question from behind the stumps. He thinks the batsman got some glove on it. Dimuth Karunaratne gets convinced and decides to take the review. The UltraEdge shows the bat is not involved, which rules out the review for caught behind. The third umpire also looks for an lbw. The Ball Tracker shows the ball is pitching outside leg. Hence, the on-field decision stands.
Darted on the pads, Joshua Da Silva looks to flick it away but misses. The ball goes out to the leg side off the pads.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva pushes it back to the bowler.
That is some turn! Such movements are keeping the fielders alive behind the stumps. Looped up, around off. Joshua Da Silva leans in and looks to defend it out but gets beaten by the turn.
Floated, full and on off. Joshua Da Silva pushes it towards short mid off.
Some more spin as Praveen Jayawickrama comes into the attack.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva steps forward and works it towards mid on for a single.
Floated, full and on middle. Joshua Da Silva prods and blocks it out solidly.
BEATEN! Tossed up, outside off. Joshua Da Silva stays back and looks to poke it out but misses.
On off, Bonner comes forward and tucks it towards mid on for a single.
Loopy ball, around leg. The ball turns away outside leg. Bonner looks to flick it away but misses.
Darted on the pads, Bonner blocks it out to short leg.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva remains solid in his defense.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva punches it to cover.
Full, around middle and off. Joshua Da Silva prods and defends it onto the pitch.
Full and on off. Da Silva remains solid in his defense.
Tossed up, on off. Joshua Da Silva blocks it out watchfully.
Floated, full and on off. Joshua Da Silva defends it out.
Full, around middle and leg. Bonner flicks it to square leg.
Full and outside off. Bonner gets behind and blocks it out.
FOUR! Nicely played. Touch short, on off. Bonner stays back and pulls it through square leg for a boundary.
Flatter and on off. Bonner pushes it towards point.
Tossed up, on off. Bonner defends it out solidly.

FOUR BYES! Some turn and bounce this time. Looped up, around leg. The ball turns away and gets some extra bounce off it, which beats the keeper behind the stumps. The ball goes towards fine leg. Free runs for West Indies and they would not mind that at all.
Full and on off. Da Silva pushes it to cover.
Full and on off. Joshua Da Silva prods and blocks it out.
Flatter, around middle. The ball spins in. Joshua Da Silva goes back and gets his bat down in time to defend it out.
Full, on the pads, Nkrumah Bonner clips it to right of mid-on for a single.
Tossed up, around off. Bonner works it to point.
Full and on middle. Nkrumah Bonner tucks it to mid-on.
Flatter and on off. Joshua Da Silva pushes it to point. West Indies are 18/6 after 12 overs.
Ramesh Mendis misses out on his Hat Trick! Looped up, around leg. Joshua Da Silva defends it out with the pads. Mendis appeals but the umpire is unmoved.

DRINKS! And breathe... The spin duo of Sri Lanka, Ramesh Mendis and Lasith Embuldeniya are enjoying themselves. They are bowling for fun right now. 18/6, it will take some miracle for West Indies to get out of this environment. Also, Joshua Da Silva walks out to bat.

OUT! TIMBER! Ramesh Mendis picks up another wicket and Holder has been sent back on a golden duck. Holder is confused how did it go through his defense. He cannot believe it. The heads are down in the West Indies dressing room. Tossed up, outside off. Holder covers his stumps and looks to defend it out but misses. The ball sneaks past the blade and clips the off pole. The spinners have strangled the West Indies batting line up. Just adding on to the agony. Ramesh Mendis is on a Hat Trick. And, for his bowling performance today, he certainly deserves it.
Commentary.Howout: b Ramesh Mendis

Commentary.Commentary: Jason Holder is the new man in.

OUT! LBW! In just 12 overs West Indies have half of their team sent back. Ramesh Mendis picks up his third wicket. An attempted off-break, around off, but it goes straight through. Mayers leaves it alone, hoping it will go past him, but the ball stays low and struck him on the pads right in front of the stumps. Mendis appeals and the umpire raises his finger in a flash. The thought about taking a review could not have passed by Kyle Mayers mind after being so exposed in front of the stumps.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ramesh Mendis

Commentary.Commentary: A single as this is eased down to long on.
Flatter and short, outside off. Mayers stays back and punches it to point for a single.
A dot to end the over! Looped up, full and on off. Bonner defends it out on the front foot. Another successful over for Lasith Embuldeniya. A wicket and just a single off it.
Mayers is off the mark. On the pads, Mayers clips it towards mid-wicket for a single.
Floated, full and on off. Mayers defends it out solidly.
Tossed up, around leg. Mayers looks to defend it out but misses. He gets rapped on the pads. Going down leg.
Kyle Mayers walks out now.

OUT! TIMBER! Sri Lanka right on top. Everything is going their way at the moment. Roston Chase gets sent back on just one run. Looped up, around off. Chase looks to defend it out but misses. The ball sneaks through the gap between the bat and the pad to castle the stumps behind. It has been all Sri Lanka in this session. West Indies lose their fourth wicket. They have absolutely no clue and are struggling here at the moment. The spinners are doing exceptionally well for Sri Lanka.
Commentary.Howout: b Lasith Embuldeniya

Commentary.Commentary: Floated, around off. Chase pushes it towards cover.
On middle, worked through mid-wicket for a single.
Looks like the rain is approaching us. The groundsmen have formed up near the covers. Hope that they don't have to get it out on the field.
Tossed up, on off, pushed to covers.
This is down the leg side. Chase blocks it with his pads.
The spinners are all over West Indies right now! Full and down on the pads. Chase misses his defensive shot and gets hit on the pads.
Very full and on middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Roston Chase to walk out at number 5.

OUT! TIMBER! West Indies in a spot of bother! A flatter ball, on middle. Shai Hope was playing for the turn but this one comes with the angle. Hope goes deep in his crease trying to flick but misses. The ball brushes his pads and hits the stumps.
Commentary.Howout: b Ramesh Mendis

Commentary.Commentary: Slightly short, on middle. Hope works it through mid-wicket. The fielder gives a chase and cuts it out near the fence. Saves a single. Three taken.
Tossed up, on middle. Hope shuffles across and blocks it out.
This one spins away sharply. Hope gets an inside edge back onto the pads.
Short and on middle. Hope flicks it straight to short square leg who shows good reflexes.
Full again, on off. Shai Hope defends it toward cover.
Full and on off, driven straight to covers.
Full and on off. Nkrumah Bonner lunges and blocks it out.
Around off, kept out.
An appeal for LBW but that was clearly missing the leg stump. Short and turning in sharply. Nkrumah Bonner misses his hit and gets hit high on the pads.
Play and a miss! Short and outside off. Nkrumah Bonner misses his cut.
Darted on the pads. Nkrumah Bonner hangs back and tries to whip it across but misses.
A loopy ball, on middle, Nkrumah Bonner tucks it to square leg.
Short and on off. Hope blocks it back on the deck.
A sharp leave by Hope. A flatter ball, just around off. Hope tries to pad it away.
Who will come out now? It is Shai Hope.
The umpire takes it upstairs to confirm a fair catch. Soft signal is OUT! The replays show Angelo Mathews has his fingers under the ball. He has to depart, as the third umpire says it is OUT.

OUT! TAKEN! What a catch by Angelo Mathews! A flatter ball, on off. Jermaine Blackwood rocks back and looks to break the shackles as he looks to heave it over the leg side but mistimes it towards mid on where Angelo Mathews dives forward and takes a sharp low catch. The umpires wanted to check it and the third umpire was satisfied with a single replay. West Indies 2 down now.
Commentary.Howout: c Angelo Mathews b Lasith Embuldeniya

Commentary.Commentary: Full and on middle. Jermaine Blackwood blocks it out.
Full and angling on middle. Jermaine Blackwood looks to defend but misses and gets hit on the pads. An appeal but nothing from the umpire.
DROPPED! A full ball, outside off, turning away. Jermaine Blackwood looks to defend but gets a thick outside edge to the first slip who lets it through his hand. Two taken.
Around off, defended towards cover. They wanted a quick single but decides against it in the end.
Flatter and on middle. Nkrumah Bonner defends it off the back foot.
A loopy ball, on off. Nkrumah Bonner defends it out.
Full and on middle. Blocked out.
Around off. Nkrumah Bonner punches off the back foot through covers for a brace.
Flatter and down leg. Kept out.
Now this one comes in with the angle. Jermaine Blackwood reads and defends it solidly.
This one spins well away. Jermaine Blackwood lets it through.
Another leave by Jermaine Blackwood as he lunges his front foot out.
Full, loopy and outside off. Jermaine Blackwood covers his off stump and leaves it alone.
FOUR! Nicely played! Flatter and around off. Jermaine Blackwood cuts it off the back foot through point for a boundary.
Full and on off. Jermaine Blackwood prods and defends it.
Full and down the leg, Left alone by Nkrumah Bonner.
Short again and down the leg side. Nkrumah Bonner misses his pull and gets hit  high on the pads. Was missing the leg pole.
Nkrumah Bonner walks out at number 3.

OUT! LBW! This was short but did not bounce as much as Brathwaite anticipated while playing the pull shot. He misses and gets high on the pads. An appeal and up goes the finger. The captain takes the review straightaway. UltraEdge shows no bat there. Three reds on Ball Tracker and Kraigg Brathwaite walks back for a 15-ball duck.
Commentary.Howout: lbw b Ramesh Mendis

Commentary.Commentary: Review! Kraigg Brathwaite decides to take a review for lbw. The onfield decision is OUT. The UltraEdge shows no bat is involved. The Ball Tracker shows three reds and Sri Lanka strike in no time. The on-field decision stands. West Indies lose their first review.
Tossed up, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite defends under his eyes.
Short and outside off, tucked to mid-wicket for a single.
Flighted ball, on middle. Jermaine Blackwood defends off the back foot.
A loopy ball, on middle. Blocked out.
Full again, on off, Kraigg Brathwaite pushes it to covers.
Full and on off, pushed to mid on for a single.
Short again, just around off. Jermaine Blackwood watchfully leaves it.
Some leave from Jermaine Blackwood as this one misses the off pole by an inch! Flatter and around off. Left alone.
Full and on middle, pushed back to the bowler.
Fuller and around off. Kraigg Brathwaite lets it through to the keeper.
Darted on the pads, flicked to square leg.
Flatter and on middle. Blocked out.
This one shoots off thre deck. Kraigg Brathwaite leaves as this one is angled down the leg side.
Short again but a quicker one, whacked to square leg.
Short and down the leg side. Jermaine Blackwood rocks back and pulls it to deep square leg for a single.
Who will bowl from the other end? Ramesh Mendis it is.
Tossed up, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite prods and blocks it out. Maiden to start for Sri Lanka.
Around off, pushed to covers.
Full and on middle. Blocked out.
A flighted ball, outside off. Kraigg Brathwaite looks to cut but misses it completely.
Flatter now, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite defends it on the leg side.
Starts with a full ball, on middle. Kraigg Brathwaite blocks it out.
